    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="386"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d386">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/7469: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chinese Minister of Finance</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kung</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="35" xml:id="d386fn35">Handed to the Acting Secretary of State by the
                        Chinese Ambassador on March 24.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-21">March 21,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I am happy to inform you that I have authorized the Universal Trading Corporation
                    to hand over the last instalment necessary for the complete repayment of the
                    Wood Oil Loan of February 8, 1939.<note n="36" xml:id="d386fn36">See
                        Generalissimo Chiang’s message of March 25, 1939, to President Roosevelt,
                            <ref target="frus1939v03#pg_659">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1939, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 659</ref>.</note> While the terms of
                    the Agreement do not require full liquidation of obligation until January 1,
                    1944, sufficient funds have accumulated to make it possible at this time.</p>
                <p>May I say that the Universal Trading Corporation’s action is an indication of
                    China’s determination to maintain its traditional policy of faithful fulfillment
                    of all its obligations. I shall also like to take this opportunity of expressing
                    our deep appreciation for United States financial assistance to China<note
                        n="37" xml:id="d386fn37">A joint statement was issued at Washington on March
                        21 when agreement was signed; see bracketed note, <ref target="#pg_490">p.
                            490</ref>.</note> which has been all the more welcome because of its
                    timeliness.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>H. H. <hi rend="smallcaps">Kung</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
